courseWork.title: Historical Event Research of Exemplary Saviors (H.E.R.O.E.S)
courseWork.description:
Research an historical event where an individual or group of individuals acted in heroic ways. Examples might include first responders from 9/11, the pilot who landed a plane on the Hudson River after a malfunction, the Capitol police officer who led rioters away from congress members and saved lives, individuals who went above and beyond to save other lives, prevent tragedy, etc. Give a summary. Do your best to answer the questions of who, what, where, when, why, and how. Use complete sentences, with proper grammar, spelling, and punctuation. 

Use your own words, do not copy and paste, especially without citing sources, as that is plagiarism. 

This assignment is to summarize a true, non-fiction historical event.

Open a new Google Doc and type your summary. Submit it here in the GC.

courseWork.title: Melody composition
courseWork.description:
Create an original (do not copy something or someone else) 8-bar melody in a music notation program of your choice. Use a program to add notes and rhythms, so that your sounds can be heard. This melody could be a part of your larger composition, but it does not have to be.

Choose a time signature (3/4 or 4/4 or larger, but not 2/4. In compound meter, 9/8 or 12/8 or larger is acceptable, but not 6/8).
Choose a scale or mode.
Compose your melody.
Be creative - Melodies have combinations of steps and skips. Melodies have rhythmic variation. Do not draw 8 whole notes in step-wise motion and call that your melody. Do not use a single note over and over for the majority of the 8 bars. Do not turn in 8 bars of rests. Any attempt to do the least amount of work possible will lead to a lowered score on this assignment.

I recommend that you think of antecedent/consequent, ending the 4th bar with something that does not sound completely resolved, and ending the 8th bar with a full resolution. Examples to refer to include Mary Had a Little Lamb, Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star, etc.

If you are new to or uncomfortable with music notation, you can use dotpiano.com to record your melody.

Turn in a sound file and/or score. Ideally, I should be able to see and hear your music.

Follow the link below to see tips for writing a melody. 

[If you are in more than one music class that has this same assignment, just do it once. I'll give credit for both classes.]

link.title: How to Write a Melody: 9 Tips for Writing Memorable Melodies - 2021 - MasterClass

courseWork.title: Heroes SP Survey
courseWork.description:
Fill out the Google Form to share your intention of what you will do to be a hero for someone.
Start the project the week of February 16 and complete it by the end of the 3rd quarter. Along the way, you can document what you did. This could be with pictures, video, or writing a summary at the end. Questions to answer include: What you chose to do as a service project, why you chose your particular service project, who it helped, how it helped them, what you learned along the way, how long you spent doing the project (examples could be 5-10 minutes daily, twice a week, etc.), and any other information that you would like to share.

You should average 15 minutes twice a week on this project. At the end of a week, you will have completed 30 minutes. At the end of 2 weeks, you should have completed an hour. At the end of 6 weeks, you should have completed at least 3 hours on this project.

courseWork.title: Extra Credit Composer/Musician Report
courseWork.description:
1. Choose a composer/musician
look up your composer/musician on any sources to which you have access (public library, internet, etc.)

2. Include the following in your written report:
    A. birth and death dates
    B. nationality and geographic location
    C. early life
    D. influenced by, or who they influenced
    E. what made that person famous
    F. list some well-known works
    G. what world events occurred during their lifetime
    H. draw a sketch of that person, by hand, and use it as your title page (take a picture of your sketch, if submitting online)
    I. include newspaper or current event items, if any (such as concert info, festival info, etc.)
    J. list other contributions to society, outside the main field
    K. style of the composer/musician (Ancient, Medieval, Renaissance, Baroque, Classical, Romantic, 20th Century, Impressionist, Folk Music, War Songs, Protest Songs, Ragtime,  ShowTunes/Broadway, Blues, Jazz, Big Band, Swing, Rock, Disco, Country Western, Electronic, Modern, World Music, Religious Music, etc.)
    L. any interesting trivia

3. Include a link to the composer’s/musician’s music, such as YouTube, etc.

4. This is a brief report
    A. keep it simple
    B. make it neat and legible
    C. 2 to 3 pages of of text is acceptable (not including the bibliography page)
    D. check spelling, punctuation, grammar, etc.
    E. Papers must be in ink or typed (double space)
    F. include title page (title, sketch of composer, your name, date)
    G. include citations (MLA format) and a bibliography of sources used
Bibliographies must include at least five sources.
1. All sources must be cited in the paper. 
2. General Histories and Textbooks are NOT suitable sources. 
3. All sources should be in English, unless you just happen to be fluent in another language.
4.  Use proper MLA bibliographic format

Do not plagiarize in an attempt to get extra credit. It will only break trust and reveal your true character.

courseWork.title: Art Project
courseWork.description:
Create an art project illustrating a leader or hero in your own family, living or deceased. Do your best to include the person's face in the project. You may include other items if they add to the significance or meaning of the person to you. 

Draw, color, paint, create digital art or animation, or create a work in other art media (depending on what supplies you have) - submit a (digital) copy of an original photo/picture, etc., as well as your completed project. You can take a picture of your artwork and submit it here, in the Google Classroom. (50 points)

Include a short write-up explaining your artistic process, from inception to completion, materials you used, obstacles you encountered, solutions to any problems that may have arisen, etc. In other words, what did you do? Who did you paint/illustrate, etc.? How did you do your art project? Why did you do it the way you did, etc.? (10 points)

courseWork.title: Letter to Leader or Hero
courseWork.description:
Write a letter to a leader or hero. Share your admiration, appreciation, and let them know how they have inspired you in your life. Think of what types of questions you might ask them or what you would like them to know about you. Ideally, you would send this letter to a leader or hero in your life, in addition to doing this as an assignment. In this time of isolation, connecting to others might be just the thing we need the most.

You can open up a Google Doc and start typing here. Alternatively, you can hand write a letter and then take a picture and submit it here.

Below are tips for writing a formal or informal letter. You will need to decide what type of letter (formal or informal) you will write. If you have never met the person, then formal is the safer option. If it is someone you know, then informal might be the way to do it.

[If you are in more than one music class that has this same assignment, just do it once. I'll give credit for both classes.]

courseWork.title: Practica Music Ch. 6 - Modes - pp. 86-93
courseWork.description:
Read the end of chapter 6, pp. 86-93, in the Practice Musica text. Practica Musica theory text can be found in the Google Classroom.
Go to Musictheory.net and click on Exercises.
Click on Scale Construction. (It's the 9th one down.)
Click on Settings (the gear icon) and choose your clef. 
Choose the following 4 modes - Ionian (same as major), Dorian, Mixolydian, Aeolian (same as minor). Or you can choose all if you would like more challenge.
Choose the first 4 key signatures with flats and the first 4 with sharps. Also, choose the key signature with no sharps or flats. This is a total of 9 scales. Or, choose more if you want more challenge.
Do 20 exercises and get a score of 90% or higher. If you need to, you can reset your score by clicking on the ellipsis (3 dots to the right of the gear icon).
When finished, click on the 3 horizontal dots and select "Show Progress Report." You will need to enter your first and last name to "sign" the report. Click on "Copy link." 
Submit (turn in) the link here, in the Google Classroom, under this assignment.
I do not need to see a screenshot, just your Progress Report.
[If you are in more than one music class that has this same assignment, just do it once. I'll give credit for both classes.]
